[h3 id=AboutTheGame 
	" About the Game
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	[em 
		"Arrow of Death Part 1
	]em
	" is part 1 of a 2-part text adventure game published in 1983 for home computers. The worshipped rod's famous glow has been stolen. It's your task to rescue it with the aid of a magical arrow. Part 1 requires you to find the whereabouts of the parts which make up the arrow. It is the 3rd installment in Brian Howarth's 
	[em 
		"Mysterious Adventures
	]em
	" series.
	$LF
]div
[pre 
	$LF
]pre
[h3 id=AboutTheTas 
	" About the TAS
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"This TAS aims to complete the game as fast as possible.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=WhySuchAMassiveImprovement 
	" Why Such a Massive Improvement?
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"This is an improvement of 12,999 frames (4:19.57) over the previous TAS. This improvement was made possible thanks to a new discovery where pressing enter without typing a command gets rid of the picture. This does make loading between typing non-directional commands a bit longer, because the game's keeping track of everything you see and own with text, but it doesn't have to load the pictures, saving up to 10 seconds or more per directional command. We press enter just before typing our first directional command (N/E/S/W/U/D/GO/CLIMB) to save a fraction of a second from not having the text load. Input ends on frame 17088 when we input the command "CUT BRAN" (CUT BRANCH).
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=WhyITookABreak 
	" Why I Took a Break
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"I'm a bit angry and embarrassed that I missed this because I had found you could disable the photo, but I just assumed the picture would return by itself. This is also a big part of what made me take a week's break - stress, low self-esteem and burnout. But I'm glad to be back at it now.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"That's all from me. Thanks for reading.
	$LF
]div
